    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Undecided and Fickle. Why Not?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lex Renda letter agrees with Alan Wolfe's Oct 22 Op-Ed bemoaning 'overemphasis' placed upon undecided voter</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I agree with Alan Wolfe when he bemoans the overemphasis placed upon the undecided voter (Op-Ed, Oct. 22). I would also add that the media's fascination with undecided and independent voters has pushed the most fundamental partisan issue in this election into the background: control of the state legislatures.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I agree with Alan Wolfe when he bemoans the overemphasis placed upon the undecided voter (Op-Ed, Oct. 22). I would also add that the media's fascination with undecided and independent voters has pushed the most fundamental partisan issue in this election into the background: control of the state legislatures.</p>
        <p>Which party controls the legislatures next year will, through the creation of district boundaries, play a huge role in determining control of the House of Representatives for the next decade.</p>
        <p>LEX RENDA  Milwaukee, Oct. 22, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an associate professor of history, University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee.</p>
      </block>
